const a = [
  {"id":9094,"text":"Which of the following negligences refers to defective hospital care and equipment, incompetent employees, and failure to maintain the standards of care?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic medicine, Topic: Medical negligence.","responses":[{"text":"Civil negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contributory negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Third party negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corporate negligence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Criminal negligence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9183,"text":"A 20-year-old male presents to the emergency department with complaints of fever, fatigue, and headache for the past 10 days. He is now experiencing agitation and hallucination, with aggressive behavior. History suggests that he suffered a dog bite 4 weeks ago. On examination, he is found to have excessive salivation, hyperreflexia, and spasticity. What is the most probable diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Herpes simplex encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rabies","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Psychosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetanus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9191,"text":"What is the treatment for acute typhoid fever?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cefotaxime","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9205,"text":"All the travelers who are exposed to the risk of yellow fever or pass through the endemic zones of yellow fever should have a valid vaccination card for yellow fever before they enter a country.  If any of them fails to possess the card, which of the following should be done?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) CDC, CDC. Isolation. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Published March 21, 2023. Accessed April 12, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/your-health/isolation.html\r\n\r\n(2) Yellow fever. Accessed April 12, 2023. https://www.who.int/news-room/questions-and-answers/item/yellow-fever","responses":[{"text":"Treated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kept in isolation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kept in quarantine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immunized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sent back","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9231,"text":"What is the gold-standard investigation for typhoid?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 260. (2) Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 151. (3) Infectious module, Microbiology lecture slides, Topic: Common microorganisms in relation to fever, Sub-topic: Lab diagnosis of Salmonella typhi.","responses":[{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urinalysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Splenic biopsy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9233,"text":"Which of the following refers to the restriction of the movement of a sick person in order to stop the spread of certain diseases?","explanation":null,"reference":"Quarantine and isolation | quarantine | cdc. Published December 27, 2021. Accessed April 12, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/index.html","responses":[{"text":"Rehabilitation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primordial prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quarantine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isolation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9257,"text":"In the case of the transfer of malaria protozoa by the mosquito, which of the following forms is transferred?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Hypnozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Merozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gametocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Schizonts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporozoites","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9281,"text":"A child presents to the clinic with fever and convulsions. The child was bitten by a dog 3 months ago. Which of the following samples must be obtained to confirm a diagnosis of rabies?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ante mortem testing | specific groups | cdc. Published January 27, 2021. Accessed April 12, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/rabies/specific_groups/hcp/ante_mortem.html","responses":[{"text":"Cerebrospinal fluid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nail clippings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9292,"text":"What is an unusual, more than expected occurrence of a disease or any event related to health, in a community, called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Principles of epidemiology | lesson 1 - section 11. Published December 20, 2021. Accessed April 12, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/csels/dsepd/ss1978/lesson1/section11.html","responses":[{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epidemic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporadic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperendemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9307,"text":"A 25-year-old male presents to the clinic with complaints of a painless ulcer on the shaft of the penis. He has no symptoms otherwise. Clinical examination reveals rubbery enlargement of bilateral inguinal lymph nodes. What is the most likely causative agent?","explanation":null,"reference":"Tudor ME, Al Aboud AM, Leslie SW, Gossman W. Syphilis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed April 20, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534780/","responses":[{"text":"Human papillomavirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Herpes simplex type 2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomonas vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9316,"text":"A 5-year-old female child is brought to the clinic with loose stools for the past 4 days. On examination, the child is irritable with skin pinch going back in 3 seconds. No other signs of dehydration are observed. What is the replacement fluid and dosage to be given as per the IMNCI protocol?","explanation":null,"reference":"WHO, UNICEF. Integrated Management Of Neonatal \u0026 Childhood Illness. 2nd ed. Ministry of National Health Services; 2019: 18.","responses":[{"text":"75 ml/kg ORS over 4 hour period","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"100 ml/kg IV Ringer's lactate every 6 hours","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100-200 ml ORS after every loose stool","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increasing frequency of breastfeeding with 100-200 ml ORS","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100 ml/kg ORS over 3 hour period","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9317,"text":"A 20-year-old unconscious male is brought to the emergency room with profuse bleeding from the incised wound on his left wrist. Which of the following types of consent will be used to treat this patient?","explanation":null,"reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 23.","responses":[{"text":"No need of consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Written consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implied consent","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expressed consent","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9437,"text":"The lawyer of the defendant calls in a ballistic expert as part of the proceedings of a suspected homicide. Which of the following is not true regarding this type of witness?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 17-18.","responses":[{"text":"Describes what he/she saw","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A doctor may be common or expert witness","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skilled in foreign law","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can volunteer a statement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Draws inference from observations","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9439,"text":"What is the correct legal terminology for a verbal statement made by a dying individual in front of a doctor narrating the circumstances leading to his/her death?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 7th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors; 2017: 14-15.","responses":[{"text":"Dying deposition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dying declaration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Documentary evidence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral evidence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compos mentis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9458,"text":"During a police encounter, a dacoit is shot dead. Who will carry out the investigation in this case?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic medicine, Topic: Legal procedures I.","responses":[{"text":"The coroner","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The police","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The magistrate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Medico-legal officer of the area","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The panchas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9464,"text":"A doctor receives 5 cases of cholera together at his private clinic in Lahore. He should report these cases to which of the following authorities?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"District nazim","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"District police station","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Local police station","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Area magistrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"District health authorities","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9508,"text":"What is the drug of choice in cestode infection?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 944.","responses":[{"text":"Diethylcarbamazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Albendazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ivermectin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrantel pamoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Praziquantel","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9511,"text":"A 36-year-old woman, with a known case of HIV infection, has a very low CD4 lymphocyte count and was prescribed treatment. She is non-compliant with her medications and now presents with shortness of breath on exertion and hypoxia. Her chest X-ray reveals fine bilateral infiltrates and the computed tomography (CT) scan reports a bilateral ground-glass appearance. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 361.","responses":[{"text":"Pneumococcal pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congestive heart failure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocystis pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Influenza","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10166,"text":"A young patient presents to the clinic with complaints of acute watery diarrhea without abdominal pain, along with vomiting. The stool is rice-watery in nature. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 154.","responses":[{"text":"Norvovirus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vibrio cholera","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amebiasis (E. histolytica)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10169,"text":"Which of the following antimalarial drugs is effective against the exo-erythrocytic form of malarial parasite?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Quinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mefloquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrimethamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloroquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10175,"text":"A 15-year-old boy comes into the emergency department. He has had a history of fever for the last 2 weeks, initially, low-grade 100 F, followed by high-grade with severe abdominal pain. His blood culture is done as an outpatient is positive for Salmonella typhi with sensitivity to azithromycin and imipenem-cilastatin. An X-ray of the abdomen, erect and supine, shows gas under the right diaphragm. What is the most common site of gut perforation in enteric fever?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Stomach perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ascending colon perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jejunum perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Duodenal perforation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ileal perforation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10186,"text":"A patient complains of having recurrent malarial infection after recovering from it once, caused by Plasmodium ovale and Plasmodium vivax. Which form of these Plasmodium species is responsible for the relapses?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Hypnozoites","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gametozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metacryptozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Merozoites","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporozoites","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10193,"text":"A convict is called numerous times to attend a trial in court, but he fails to appear. Ultimately the court orders a summons to be put outside his house. Which of the following describes a summons?","explanation":null,"reference":"Subrahmanyam, B. V. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed., CBS Publishers, 2019: 9-10.","responses":[{"text":"A warrant to arrest the person and present them in the court","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Letter to a person to appear in court for evidence or any other reason","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"A letter that can only issued by the magistrate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A rectangular scripture to call upon an entity for assistance","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A fee tendered to cover court expenses","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10232,"text":"A doctor is called in sessions court as a witness. During cross-examination, he utters an indecent remark on the defense counsel, which is brought to the knowledge of the judge who gives minimum punishment to the doctor. Which of the following would it be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic-medicine, Topic: Legal procedures 1.","responses":[{"text":"Fee of Rs. 10 only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fee of Rs. 100 only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Warning in writing with copy to the employer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Detaining him in the court till rising of the court for the day","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fee of Rs. 50 only","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10242,"text":"A young male develops a high-grade fever intermittent in nature and occurring every 48 hours. Later on, his laboratory report reveals that he has vivax malaria. Which subtype fever does he have?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 154.","responses":[{"text":"Quotidian fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quartan fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Relapsing fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertian fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant tertian fever","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10264,"text":"A 16-year-old male presents with a complaint of high-grade fever with chills and rigors for five days along with severe body aches and pains. On peripheral examination, the patient is febrile. On systemic examination, no significant finding was found except his petechial rashes all over the extremities. What would the most likely diagnosis be?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 287.","responses":[{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10363,"text":"Which of the following is an appropriate drug in the treatment of acute enteric fever?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 260-261.","responses":[{"text":"Ampicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sulphonamide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10364,"text":"The present-day societies have high expectations from medical professionals regarding their ideal ethical practice. The broader guidelines can be learned from the subject of medical ethics. What does this subject deal with?","explanation":null,"reference":"Markose A, Krishnan R, Ramesh M. Medical ethics. Journal of Pharmacy \u0026 Bioallied Sciences. Published October 2016. Accessed April 7, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5074007/","responses":[{"text":"Implied contract and its details","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Research ethics should be made mandatory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Confidentiality of patient record as an ideal ethical practice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Moral values to be observed by medical professional in their practice","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Interpersonal relationships are the basic requirement","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10406,"text":"For which of the following disorders is chloroquine used as an anti-inflammatory drug?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 650.","responses":[{"text":"Intestinal amebiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rheumatoid arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Babesiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatic amebiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11398,"text":"Which of the following drugs acts by increasing the GABA activity?","explanation":null,"reference":"Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 941.","responses":[{"text":"Pyrantel pamoate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diethylcarbamazine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ivermectin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Praziquantel","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Niclosamide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11437,"text":"Leaving gauze in abdominal surgery comes under which negligence?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic medicine, Topic: Laws of medical men III.","responses":[{"text":"Civil negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Criminal negligence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd party negligence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corporate misconduct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Corporate negligence","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11458,"text":"A 6-year-old child took his father's pistol to show to his friends but the pistol accidentally went off. One of his friends got injured. Under the law, the child is considered as which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic medicine, Topic: Legal procedures I.","responses":[{"text":"Guilty","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Unfit to plead","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Not sane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Not criminally responsible","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diminished responsible","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11460,"text":"A 35-year-old diabetic patient presents to the outpatient department with complaints of fever associated with rigor and chills and increased frequency of urine. There are no other significant findings. What is the most probable cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 131-132.","responses":[{"text":"Urinary tract infection","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Viral fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11463,"text":"A patient in the hospital was on the ventilator and got treated for an illness with clindamycin, ethambutol, and some other antibiotics. He then got extubated and was started on meropenem 10 days ago. Two days ago he presented with watery diarrhea suggesting a C. difficile infection. How will this condition be managed?","explanation":null,"reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 311.","responses":[{"text":"IV vancomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stop all antibiotics and send stool sample for ova and parasite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stop meropenem and give oral metronidazole","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral vancomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV metronidazole","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11494,"text":"Zieman dots with basket forms and occasional band forms of plasmodium are seen in which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":"https://www.cdc.gov/dpdx/resources/pdf/benchAids/malaria/Pmalariae_benchaidV2.pdf","responses":[{"text":"Plasmodium ovale","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium knowlesi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium malariae","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium vivax","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11499,"text":"At what CD4+ count of a patient with human immunodeficiency virus do AIDS-defining illnesses emerge?","explanation":null,"reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 173.","responses":[{"text":"\u003c 50 CD4+ cells/mm3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 200 CD4+ cells/mm3","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 150 CD4+ cells/mm3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 100 CD4+ cells/mm3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"\u003c 250 CD4+ cells/mm3","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12291,"text":"A 20-year-old female presented to the outpatient department with a complaint of fever on alternate days, documented to be 103-104 °F, along with sweating and chills. She also had malaise, vomiting, weakness, muscle pain, and headache. She was pale and had a palpable spleen on examination. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":"The symptoms of fever on alternate days with high temperatures, sweating, chills, malaise, vomiting, weakness, and muscle pain are classic indicators of **malaria**. The palpable spleen on examination also suggests an enlarged spleen, a common finding in malaria cases.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 424.","responses":[{"text":"Dengue fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Malaria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoebiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trypanosomiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid fever","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12292,"text":"A 7-year-old boy is brought to the outpatient department with a complaint of fever and vesicular rashes all over the body. The vesicles appear in bunches and some are in the healing phase. There is a history of sore throat and cough too. What is the long-term complication of the condition at a later age?","explanation":"The boy's presentation of fever and vesicular rashes, especially in clusters, along with a history of sore throat and cough, is indicative of chickenpox, caused by the varicella-zoster virus (VZV). Chickenpox is a common childhood infection characterized by these symptoms and is typically self-limiting in children.\r\n\r\nHowever, VZV can remain dormant in the body's nerve cells after the initial chickenpox infection and may reactivate later in life, leading to **shingles or herpes zoster**. Shingles is characterized by painful, blistering rashes that often appear in a band-like pattern on one side of the body. The reactivation of VZV can occur years or even decades after the initial infection, and it is more common in older individuals or those with weakened immune systems.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 285.","responses":[{"text":"Zoster/shingles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atypical pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otitis media","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12293,"text":"A 14-year-old girl presents to the clinic with a complaint of a hypopigmented patch on her face. On examination, it is a well-demarcated area of skin that does not respond to pain stimuli. How is the condition diagnosed?","explanation":"The condition described is suggestive of leprosy, particularly tuberculoid leprosy. The diagnosis of leprosy, caused by *Mycobacterium leprae*, is typically confirmed using **acid-fast staining** of skin lesions or nasal scrapings.\r\n\r\nAcid-fast staining is a crucial diagnostic tool in identifying *Mycobacterium leprae*, the bacterium responsible for leprosy. This staining technique is unique in its ability to stain mycobacteria, which have a high lipid content in their cell walls, making them resistant to conventional staining methods. In acid-fast staining, mycobacteria retain the dye even after being washed with an acid solution, hence the term \"acid-fast.\"","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 184-185.","responses":[{"text":"Acid-fast staining","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"India ink staining","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Darkfield staining","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified acid-fast staining","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram staining","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12294,"text":"A 6-day-old neonate is brought to the pediatric emergency with a history of fits and refusal to take feed. The fits are more severe on exposure to light and excessive sound. The neonate was delivered at home. What is the causative organism?","explanation":"The symptoms described, such as fits (or seizures) and exaggerated responses to light and sound, are indicative of **tetanus**, a potentially life-threatening condition caused by the neurotoxin produced by *Clostridium tetani*.\r\n\r\nTetanus typically occurs as a result of contamination of wounds, especially in unclean or home deliveries. The spores of Clostridium tetani are present in soil and can enter the body through open wounds or umbilical stumps in neonates. Once inside the body, the spores can germinate and release the potent tetanus toxin.\r\n\r\nThe tetanus toxin affects the nervous system, leading to symptoms like muscle stiffness, spasms, and seizures. In neonates, it's known as \"neonatal tetanus\" and can result from unhygienic delivery practices.","reference":"Khan, Parvez Akbar. Basis of Pediatrics. 10th ed., Paramount Books (Pvt.) Ltd, 2018: 205.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacillus anthracis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium tetani","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12334,"text":"Salmonella typhi is transmitted by the orofecal route and is the causative agent of typhoid fever. What is the primary site of infection?","explanation":"*Salmonella typhi* is transmitted through the orofecal route, typically via contaminated food or water. Upon ingestion, the bacteria make their way to the small intestine, where they initially infect the **mononuclear phagocytic cells in the Peyer's patches,** which are specialized lymphoid tissue in the intestinal wall. These cells serve as a key entry point for the bacteria.\r\n\r\nFrom there, the bacteria can enter the bloodstream and spread to various organs, including the **liver,** spleen, and bone marrow. In the liver, *Salmonella typhi* can infect mononuclear phagocytic cells, contributing to the systemic nature of the infection.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 150.","responses":[{"text":"Mononuclear phagocytic cells in the liver and spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mononuclear phagocytic cells in the liver and Peyer's patches","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mononuclear phagocytic cells in the spleen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mononuclear phagocytic cells in the large intestine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mononuclear phagocytic cells in the liver","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12335,"text":"Shigella dysenteriae causes fever, abdominal pain, and bloody diarrhea in humans. The infection is due to the release of Shiga toxin, which promotes tissue invasion in the large intestine. What is another name for Shiga toxin?","explanation":"The shiga **enterotoxin** specifically targets the intestinal epithelium and disrupts protein synthesis, leading to cell death and inflammation. The action of the toxin in the large intestine results in the characteristic symptoms of dysentery, including bloody diarrhea.\r\n\r\nEnterotoxins are a subclass of exotoxins and are named for their effect on the intestines (entero- referring to the intestinal tract). These toxins primarily affect the gastrointestinal system, causing symptoms like vomiting and diarrhea. \r\n\r\nNeurotoxins affect the nervous system, cytotoxins damage various cell types, and endotoxins are part of the outer membrane of the cell wall of Gram-negative bacteria.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 152.","responses":[{"text":"Neurotoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endotoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterotoxin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotoxin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotoxin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12336,"text":"A 25-year-old fisherman presented to the outpatient department with complaints of abdominal discomfort and diarrhea. His complete blood picture showed megaloblastic anemia and his stool had numerous oval operculated brown eggs. Which parasite is the cause of his condition?","explanation":"*Diphyllobothrium latum*, commonly known as the fish tapeworm, is a type of intestinal parasitic flatworm. It is one of the largest tapeworms that can infect humans and is typically acquired by consuming raw or undercooked freshwater fish. The eggs of Diphyllobothrium latum are passed in the stool and are often characterized by their oval shape and operculated appearance.\r\n\r\nUpon ingestion of contaminated fish, the larvae of Diphyllobothrium latum can develop into adult tapeworms in the human intestines. These tapeworms can cause various symptoms, including abdominal discomfort, diarrhea, and megaloblastic anemia, due to competition for vitamin B12 absorption in the intestine.\r\n\r\nTreatment typically involves the administration of an antiparasitic medication, such as praziquantel, to eliminate the tapeworm infection. Additionally, vitamin B12 supplementation may be necessary to address the anemia associated with this condition.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 445.","responses":[{"text":"Taenia saginata","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diphyllobothrium latum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterobius vermicularis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echinococcus granulosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ancylostoma duodenale","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12374,"text":"A 15-year-old boy presented to the outpatient department with fever, rash, and conjunctivitis. The rash appeared first on the face and then spread to the extremities including the palms and soles. Which viral infection is the boy suffering from?","explanation":"**Measles,** caused by the measles virus (a paramyxovirus), typically presents with a characteristic set of symptoms. The key features in this case include fever, rash, and conjunctivitis. One of the hallmark signs of measles is the appearance of a rash that starts on the face and then spreads to the extremities, including the palms and soles of the feet. This pattern is often referred to as a \"morbilliform\" or \"maculopapular\" rash.\r\n\r\nHerpes infections can cause different types of lesions, including cold sores and genital herpes, but they typically do not produce this specific type of rash. Rubella (German measles) can also cause a rash, but it tends to start on the trunk and spread outward. Mumps primarily presents with parotitis (swelling of the salivary glands), which is not mentioned in this case. Varicella (chickenpox) usually presents with a vesicular rash.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 312.","responses":[{"text":"Rubella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Varicella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Herpes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12375,"text":"A 45-year-old man presented to the outpatient department with fever, constipation, and abdominal tenderness. Blood culture showed growth of non-lactose fermenting (colorless) gram-negative bacteria on MacConkey's agar and the production of hydrogen sulfide gas on TSI agar. What is the probable diagnosis?","explanation":"**Typhoid fever** is caused by *Salmonella typhi*, a gram-negative bacterium. The characteristics of non-lactose fermenting colonies on MacConkey's agar and hydrogen sulfide production on TSI agar are typical for Salmonella species, including *Salmonella typhi*. The clinical presentation of fever, constipation, and abdominal tenderness aligns with the common symptoms of typhoid fever.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 151.","responses":[{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterocolitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid fever","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12377,"text":"A 35-year-old female presented with fever, chills, sweating, weakness, and headache, presumptively diagnosed as 'viral syndrome'. The patient's condition later deteriorated with altered level of consciousness, severe anemia, renal failure, and multisystem failure. Blood sample investigation showed malarial parasite. Crescent or sausage (banana) shaped gametocytes are a characteristic of which plasmodium species?","explanation":"Malaria, caused by various species of the Plasmodium parasite, presents with a wide range of symptoms and severity. **Plasmodium falciparum** is the most deadly of the known species that infect humans. One of its distinctive features is the presence of banana-shaped gametocytes in the peripheral blood, which can be seen under a microscope. These gametocytes are a crucial stage in the life cycle of the parasite, as they are responsible for transmission to the Anopheles mosquito vector when it takes a blood meal.\r\n\r\nThe patient's presentation with fever, chills, weakness, and headache is consistent with malaria, a common symptomatology of Plasmodium falciparum infection. However, the severe complications such as altered consciousness, severe anemia, renal failure, and multisystem failure highlight the dangerous nature of this particular species.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 425.","responses":[{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium knowlesi","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium malariae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium vivax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium ovale","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12378,"text":"Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) can frequently be observed in patients with severe inflammatory response and has a poor prognosis. Coagulation pathway activation leads to small vessels occlusion leading to various organ failure symptoms. Which of the following laboratory tests is used for evidence of DIC?","explanation":"DIC is a complex and potentially life-threatening condition characterized by the widespread activation of the clotting cascade, which can lead to both excessive blood clotting (thrombosis) and bleeding (hemorrhage) simultaneously. It is often associated with severe inflammatory responses, infections, trauma, or underlying diseases.\r\n\r\n**D-dimer** is a specific marker for the breakdown of fibrin clots in the body. When DIC occurs, there is an increased production of fibrin clots that subsequently break down. This breakdown releases D-dimer fragments into the bloodstream. Therefore, elevated D-dimer levels are indicative of ongoing fibrinolysis, which is a key feature of DIC.\r\n\r\nWhile other laboratory tests, such as platelet count and prothrombin time, can also provide valuable information in diagnosing DIC, D-dimer is particularly useful due to its high sensitivity in detecting fibrinolysis and its association with this complex coagulation disorder.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 35.","responses":[{"text":"Platelet count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serum calcitonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C-reactive protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"D-dimer","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12380,"text":"Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) attacks the immune system and if untreated, can cause acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS). HIV has several structural and non-structural proteins that play a role in infectivity. Which of the following is a structural gene of HIV?","explanation":"The **Gag** gene encodes structural proteins that are essential for the formation and assembly of the viral particle. These structural proteins include core proteins such as capsid (CA), matrix (MA), and nucleocapsid (NC). The Gag protein is responsible for the formation of the immature viral particle and plays a significant role in the early stages of viral replication.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 367.","responses":[{"text":"Nef","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gag","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vif","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rev","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12397,"text":"Which of the following antiviral drugs inhibits the synthesis of viral DNA?","explanation":"**Acyclovir** is an antiviral medication primarily used to treat infections caused by herpes viruses, including herpes simplex viruses (HSV) and varicella-zoster virus (VZV). Its mechanism of action involves selective inhibition of viral DNA synthesis within infected host cells.\r\n\r\nOnce acyclovir is inside the infected cell, it is phosphorylated by viral and cellular enzymes to its active form, acyclovir triphosphate. This active form competes with deoxyguanosine triphosphate (dGTP) for incorporation into the growing viral DNA chain. However, once incorporated, acyclovir effectively acts as a chain terminator, preventing further elongation of the viral DNA strand.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 442.","responses":[{"text":"Amantadine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acyclovir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"All of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Saquinavir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interferon","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12399,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct about the mechanism of action of mebendazole?","explanation":"The correct mechanism of action of mebendazole involves **inhibiting microtubule synthesis in helminths, leading to the irreversible impairment of glucose uptake**. This disruption of microtubules affects the structural integrity and function of the helminth's cells, ultimately causing their death.\r\n\r\nMebendazole does this by binding to the helminth's beta-tubulin subunits, which are essential for microtubule assembly. This binding interferes with the normal microtubule formation, preventing the helminth from maintaining its cytoskeletal structure and essential cellular processes.\r\n\r\nAs a result, the helminth is unable to absorb nutrients, particularly glucose, which is vital for its survival and energy production. This leads to a progressive depletion of energy reserves and eventual death of the parasite.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 618.","responses":[{"text":"Blocks acetylcholine transmission at the myoneural junction resulting in paralysis of helminths.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits oxidative phosphorylation in some species of helminths.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibits microtubule synthesis in helminths and causes irreversible impairment of glucose uptake.","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Increases cell membrane permeability for calcium ions, resulting in paralysis, dislodgement, and death of helminths.","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12400,"text":"Which drug is the most effective in treating systemic fungal infections in patients with acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS)?","explanation":"**Amphotericin B** is an antifungal medication known for its broad-spectrum activity against a wide range of fungal pathogens, including those that can cause severe systemic infections in immunocompromised individuals like AIDS patients.\r\n\r\nAmphotericin B works by binding to the fungal cell membrane, disrupting its integrity, and causing leakage of cellular components. This mechanism of action makes it effective against a variety of fungal species, including Candida, Aspergillus, and Cryptococcus, which can be opportunistic pathogens in AIDS patients.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that Amphotericin B can have significant side effects, including kidney toxicity, so its use requires careful monitoring and administration. In some cases, lipid formulations of Amphotericin B may be used to reduce the risk of renal toxicity.","reference":"Laverdière M. Systemic antifungal drugs: Are we making any progress? Can J Infect Dis. 1994;5(2):59-61. Accessed November 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3307410/","responses":[{"text":"Itraconazole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Flucytosine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amphotericin B","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Griseofulvin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12401,"text":"Which antimalarial drug can cause blackwater fever?","explanation":"**Quinine** is the antimalarial drug known to cause a condition called **blackwater fever**. \r\n\r\nBlackwater fever is characterized by several features. It involves the destruction of red blood cells (hemolysis), leading to the release of hemoglobin into the bloodstream. One of the hallmark symptoms is the passage of dark or black-colored urine, which results from the presence of hemoglobin breakdown products in the urine. Additionally, hemolysis can lead to jaundice, characterized by yellowing of the skin and the whites of the eyes due to the accumulation of bilirubin. \r\n\r\nIt's important to note that not everyone who takes quinine will develop blackwater fever. This condition is more commonly associated with quinine use for treating severe or drug-resistant malaria, particularly caused by the Plasmodium falciparum parasite. Therefore, quinine's use is closely monitored, and patients taking it should be observed for any signs or symptoms of blackwater fever.","reference":"(1) Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 924.\r\n\r\n(2) Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Pharmacology, Topic: Antimalarial drugs.","responses":[{"text":"Mefloquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyremethamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artemisinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Quinine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12402,"text":"Which antimalarial drug is used for causal prophylaxis?","explanation":"**Primaquine** is an important medication in the prevention and treatment of malaria, especially for *Plasmodium vivax* and *Plasmodium ovale* infections. Causal prophylaxis refers to the prevention of relapse caused by the dormant liver-stage forms of these parasites.\r\n\r\nPrimaquine is unique in its ability to target and eliminate the hypnozoites (dormant liver-stage parasites) of P. vivax and P. ovale. These hypnozoites can remain dormant in the liver for extended periods and later cause relapses of the disease. Primaquine is specifically used to prevent these relapses by killing the dormant forms.\r\n\r\nDo note that primaquine should be used with caution, as it can cause hemolysis in individuals with glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) deficiency. G6PD deficiency is a genetic condition that affects red blood cell function. Therefore, primaquine administration requires screening for G6PD deficiency and careful monitoring to prevent hemolysis in susceptible individuals.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 607. (2) Malaria prophylaxis. Malaria Site. Published February 28, 2015. Accessed November 10, 2022. https://www.malariasite.com/prophylaxis/","responses":[{"text":"Quinidine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amodiaquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyrimethamine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mefloquine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12403,"text":"Which of the following is/are an unwanted effect(s) of aminoglycosides?","explanation":"**Aminoglycosides** are a class of antibiotics that can be highly effective against a variety of bacterial infections, particularly those caused by Gram-negative bacteria. However, they are associated with several unwanted side effects, with **ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity** being among the most significant concerns.\r\n\r\n**Ototoxicity** refers to the potential for aminoglycosides to cause damage to the inner ear, leading to hearing loss, tinnitus (ringing in the ears), and balance problems. This side effect is particularly worrisome because it can be irreversible.\r\n\r\n**Nephrotoxicity** involves kidney damage and impairment of renal function, which can lead to acute kidney injury and electrolyte imbalances.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 391.","responses":[{"text":"Dry cough","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pancytopenia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ototoxicity, nephrotoxicity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatotoxicity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Irritation of gastrointestinal mucosa","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12404,"text":"Which antibiotic is safe to use for respiratory tract infections during the first trimester of pregnancy?","explanation":"**Penicillin** antibiotics, including penicillin G and amoxicillin, are often the preferred choice for treating various infections in pregnant women. They have a long history of safe use and are not associated with an increased risk of birth defects or other adverse outcomes when used during pregnancy.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, **Doxycycline** and **Fluoroquinolones** should be avoided during pregnancy, especially in the first trimester, as they can have harmful effects on fetal development and may lead to problems with the development of the baby's teeth and bones.","reference":"Lim WS, Macfarlane JT, Colthorpe CL. Treatment of community-acquired lower respiratory tract infections during pregnancy. American Journal of Respiratory Medicine: Drugs, Devices, and Other Interventions. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14720004/","responses":[{"text":"Doxycycline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluoroquinolones","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptomycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12405,"text":"Which antibiotic can cause grey baby syndrome?","explanation":"Grey baby syndrome is a rare but potentially life-threatening condition that occurs in newborns and infants when they are exposed to high levels of **chloramphenicol**.\r\nThis can result in symptoms such as a grayish-blue skin discoloration, vomiting, difficulty feeding, and in severe cases, can lead to respiratory distress, circulatory collapse, and death.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 394.","responses":[{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cephalosporin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aminoglycosides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12406,"text":"Which drug is the first line agent in the treatment of syphilis?","explanation":"Syphilis is a sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium *Treponema pallidum*. **Benzathine penicillin G** is the preferred treatment because it provides a long-lasting effect with a single injection, ensuring patient compliance with the full course of treatment.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 195.","responses":[{"text":"Macrolides","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cephalosporin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amphotericin B","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Benzathine penicillin G","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetracycline","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12407,"text":"Which of the following is another name for visceral leishmaniasis?","explanation":"**Visceral leishmaniasis**, commonly known as **Kala-azar**, is a severe form of leishmaniasis caused by the protozoan parasite *Leishmania donovani*. This disease primarily affects the visceral organs such as the spleen, liver, and bone marrow. The term \"Kala-azar\" originates from the Hindi language, meaning \"black fever,\" referring to the characteristic darkening of the skin seen in some patients with this condition.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 409.","responses":[{"text":"Cyclosporiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptosporidiosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kala-azar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mucocutaneous leishmaniasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12408,"text":"Which test is helpful in the diagnosis of giardiasis?","explanation":"Giardiasis is an intestinal infection caused by the protozoan *Giardia lamblia*, and it presents with symptoms like diarrhea, abdominal pain, and bloating. The **string test**, also known as the Enterotest or the duodenal string test, is a diagnostic procedure used to detect the presence of *Giardia lamblia* in the upper part of the small intestine.\r\n\r\nDuring the string test, the patient swallows a capsule attached to a long string. One end of the string hangs outside the mouth, and the capsule travels down to the small intestine. After a period, typically several hours, the string is slowly withdrawn. The portion of the string that was in the small intestine is then examined microscopically for the presence of Giardia trophozoites or cysts.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 415.","responses":[{"text":"Stool for occult blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"String test","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine culture","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12409,"text":"Human cysticercosis is acquired by the ingestion of which of the following?","explanation":"Cysticercosis is a parasitic infection caused by the larval stage of *Taenia solium*, a tapeworm. This condition typically occurs when individuals ingest the eggs of *Taenia solium*, which are found in contaminated food or water.\r\n\r\n*Taenia solium* eggs are shed in the feces of infected individuals, usually those who have an intestinal tapeworm infection. If proper sanitation practices are not followed, the eggs can contaminate food, water, or surfaces. Once ingested, these eggs hatch into larvae in the intestines. The larvae can then migrate to various tissues and organs in the body, including the muscles, brain, and eyes, where they develop into cysts.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 441.","responses":[{"text":"Aspergillosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporotrichosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Echinococcus granulosus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taenia solium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptococcosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12410,"text":"Ova of Schistosoma haematobium can be detected in which of the following?","explanation":"*Schistosoma haematobium* is a parasitic flatworm that causes a disease known as urinary schistosomiasis. In this disease, the adult worms reside in the blood vessels surrounding the bladder and lay their eggs. These eggs can then pass into the urinary tract and are excreted in the urine of infected individuals.\r\n\r\nThe presence of Schistosoma haematobium eggs in **urine** is a key diagnostic feature of urinary schistosomiasis. These eggs are often identified through microscopic examination of a patient's urine sample.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 453.","responses":[{"text":"Ascitic fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12411,"text":"A 45-year-old patient presents with right-sided focal fits. History reveals that he is an AIDS (acquired immunodeficiency syndrome) patient. Magnetic resonance imaging shows multiple ring-enhancing lesions in the cortical grey-white matter of the brain. What is the cause of fits?","explanation":"**CNS toxoplasmosis** is a common opportunistic infection in individuals with AIDS. It is caused by the protozoan parasite *Toxoplasma gondii*. This parasite can infect the brain and lead to the formation of multiple ring-enhancing lesions on imaging, which are characteristic findings. These lesions can cause various neurological symptoms, including focal seizures, as seen in this patient.\r\n\r\nWhile other conditions like encephalitis, peripheral neuropathy, progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy, and meningitis can also occur in AIDS patients and may present with neurological symptoms, the combination of multiple ring-enhancing brain lesions is a hallmark of CNS toxoplasmosis.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 320.","responses":[{"text":"Encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"CNS toxoplasmosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Peripheral neuropathy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12412,"text":"A 50-year-old male HIV patient is being evaluated for AIDS-defining diseases. Which of the following is not an AIDS-defining illness?","explanation":"AIDS-defining illnesses are specific conditions that occur in individuals with HIV infection and signify the progression to acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS). These illnesses often indicate severe immunosuppression. The CDC (Centers for Disease Control and Prevention) has established a list of AIDS-defining conditions. \r\nKaposi Sarcoma is an AIDS-defining malignancy that causes skin lesions and can affect other organs. It is associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) and is a common AIDS-defining illness. \r\nCMV Retinitis is cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis, a vision-threatening infection of the retina, and is considered an AIDS-defining illness. \r\nPneumocystis jiroveci Pneumonia (PCP) is a severe lung infection caused by the fungus Pneumocystis jiroveci and is one of the earliest and most common AIDS-defining illnesses. \r\n\r\nWhile **oral candidiasis** is a common opportunistic infection in individuals with HIV, it is not classified as an AIDS-defining illness.","reference":"Table: aids-defining illnesses. MSD Manual Professional Edition. Accessed November 10, 2022. https://www.msdmanuals.com/professional/multimedia/table/aids-defining-illnesses","responses":[{"text":"Oral candidiasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"CMV retinitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kaposi sarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocystis jiroveci pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal candidiasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12413,"text":"A 50-year-old female sustained injury from rusty metal on her right finger while cleaning. She is cautious and seeks emergency treatment. You washed her wound with normal saline and dressed it. Which infection is she at risk of acquiring?","explanation":"*Clostridium tetani* is the causative bacterium of tetanus, a potentially life-threatening infection commonly associated with puncture wounds contaminated with soil or rusty objects. The spores of *Clostridium tetani* can be found in soil and dust, and when introduced into deep wounds, especially those caused by puncture injuries, they can germinate and produce a potent neurotoxin called tetanospasmin. This neurotoxin can lead to muscle stiffness and spasms, often starting with the muscles around the wound and progressing to involve other muscles, including those responsible for breathing, which can be fatal if left untreated.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 656.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium tetani","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium sordelli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12414,"text":"A 25-year-old male had a sexual contact with a commercial sex worker during his business trip to UAE. He developed a painless ulcer at the penile shaft after one week. What investigation will diagnose the genital ulcer?","explanation":"**Darkfield microscopy** is a highly specific and sensitive method for diagnosing syphilis. It allows for the direct visualization of Treponema pallidum, the causative agent of syphilis, in the ulcer sample. Syphilis often presents as a painless genital ulcer, making darkfield microscopy an appropriate choice for diagnosis.\r\n\r\nHSV PCR of blood may not be the most suitable method for diagnosing a genital ulcer, as it is primarily used to detect the presence of herpes simplex virus in the blood.\r\n\r\nRPR with titer is a blood test used to screen for syphilis, but it may not provide a definitive diagnosis on its own and is typically used in combination with other tests.\r\n\r\nTzank smear on tissue biopsy from the ulcer, while useful for diagnosing certain viral infections like herpes, may not be the most appropriate initial test for a painless genital ulcer in this case.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 193, 194.","responses":[{"text":"RPR with titer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Darkfield microscopy on genital ulcer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HSV PCR of blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tzank smear on tissue biopsy from the ulcer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12415,"text":"Faisal experienced a car accident which caused him multiple injuries on the face. What are injuries on the face termed as?","explanation":null,"reference":"The pakistan penal code, 1860. Accessed November 11, 2022. http://www.pljlawsite.com/html/ppc337.htm","responses":[{"text":"Daman","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghair jaiffah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Jaiffah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jurh","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12416,"text":"During a police encounter, an armed robber shot the policeman in his abdomen. What is this penetrating injury termed as?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ghayer-jaifah, it’s Kinds and Punishment. Accessed November 11, 2022. http://thelawstudy.blogspot.com/2017/11/ghayer-jaifah-its-kinds-and-punishment.html","responses":[{"text":"Jaiffah","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Jurh","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ghair jaiffah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shajjah","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Daman","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12417,"text":"A 20-year-old came to you with the complaint of abdominal pain and vomiting. What type of consent will you take before starting physical examination?","explanation":"For a physical examination, especially in a non-emergency setting, **implied consent** is typically sufficient and is understood when a patient voluntarily comes to a healthcare provider for treatment and is aware that a physical examination is part of the diagnostic process. Implied consent is assumed when a patient presents themselves for care and cooperates with the examination.\r\n\r\nInformed consent is necessary for procedures that carry a significant risk of harm or for invasive procedures. Written consent is a form of informed consent that is documented in writing, detailing the understanding and agreement of the patient regarding the procedure and its risks. Blanket consent refers to a broad, general agreement to treatment and is not specific to any one procedure; it is not considered best practice for specific treatments or procedures. Expressed consent is given explicitly, either orally or in writing, but is not typically required for routine physical examinations.","reference":"Subrahmanyam BV. Parikh’s Textbook of Medical Jurisprudence, Forensic Medicine and Toxicology for Classrooms and Courtrooms. 8th ed. CBS Publishers; 2019: 31-32.","responses":[{"text":"Implied","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Blanket","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expressed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Written","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Informed","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12418,"text":"An injured person presented to the emergency with a broken leg and internal fixation was done by a doctor in the operation theatre. The patient was advised to rest for two weeks but he started walking in a couple of days and developed misalignment of the fractured bone. The given explanation best corresponds to which of the following?","explanation":"**Contributory negligence** occurs when the patient contributes to the harm or injury they suffer due to their own negligence or failure to follow medical advice.\r\n\r\nIn this case, the patient was advised to rest for two weeks to allow proper healing after the surgical fixation of the broken leg. However, the patient neglected this advice and started walking a few days post-surgery, which directly contributed to the misalignment of the fractured bone. This action by the patient can be seen as a failure to take reasonable care for their own safety and well-being, which contributed to the worsening of their condition.\r\n\r\nRes ipsa loquitor (the thing speaks for itself) is applied when the injury could not have occurred without negligence, but it's clear that in this case, the patient's actions played a role.\r\nTherapeutic misadventure refers to an unexpected result occurring during appropriate medical treatment.\r\nNovus actus interveniens refers to a new intervening act that breaks the chain of causation.\r\nVicarious liability refers to a situation where someone is held responsible for the actions or omissions of another person, such as an employer for their employees.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 20.","responses":[{"text":"Res ipsa loquitor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vicarious liability","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Contributary negligence","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Novus actus interveniens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic misadventure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12419,"text":"An 8-year-old child suffered from a minor injury during a picnic off from home. The teacher gave the consent for the treatment because of the absence of parents/guardians of the child. Which doctrine is applied here?","explanation":"The **Doctrine of loco parentis** refers to the legal concept where an individual or entity, such as a teacher, assumes the role of a parent or guardian temporarily, especially in situations where parents or legal guardians are not present. In this case, the teacher took on the responsibility of supervising and caring for the child during the picnic, effectively acting as a surrogate parent in the absence of the child's parents or guardians.\r\n\r\nUnder this doctrine, the teacher had the authority to provide consent for the child's medical treatment because they were acting in the best interest of the child's well-being. It allows for responsible adults, such as teachers or school personnel, to make decisions on behalf of a child when necessary to ensure their safety and health.","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 24.","responses":[{"text":"Doctrine of informed consent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctrine of therapeutic privilege","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctrine of loco parentis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctrine of full disclosure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctrine of emergency","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12420,"text":"A 30-year-old married man is suffering from scabies. The doctor who treated his illness disclosed the information to his wife. What is this an example of?","explanation":"In the context of medical ethics and legal principles, **privileged communication** refers to the confidentiality between a healthcare provider and their patient. This confidentiality is a fundamental aspect of the doctor-patient relationship, where patients are encouraged to share their medical history, symptoms, and concerns openly with the assurance that this information will be kept confidential.\r\n\r\nHowever, there are specific circumstances in which this privilege can be breached, such as when there is a risk to public health or when required by law. In this case, the doctor disclosed the scabies diagnosis to the patient's wife, possibly due to concerns about transmission within the household (community risk).","reference":"Biswas G. Review of Forensic Medicine and Toxicology. 3rd ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers; 2015: 10.","responses":[{"text":"Professional secrecy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interest of state","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Community risk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Privileged communication","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Therapeutic privilege","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12424,"text":"A 4-year-old boy came to the outpatient department with fever for fifteen days. On examination, he was lethargic and pale, temperature was 101 °F, heart rate was 110 beats/min, and respiratory rate was 30 breaths/min. Abdominal examination showed hepatosplenomegaly. Rest of the examination was unremarkable. What is the most appropriate investigation to reach the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 260.","responses":[{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine detailed report","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12425,"text":"A 15-month-old girl was brought to the outpatient department with the complaint of high-grade fever and runny nose since three days. On examination, her temperature was 102 °F, heart rate was 120 beats/min, and respiratory rate was 35 breaths/min. She had a maculopapular rash all over the body, purulent discharge from the eyes, and oral thrush. Rest of the examination was unremarkable. What is the most appropriate treatment?","explanation":"This presentation is suggestive of **measles,** a highly contagious viral illness characterized by fever, cough, runny nose (coryza), conjunctivitis, and a characteristic rash. **Vitamin A supplementation** is recommended in the management of measles, especially in children, as it has been shown to reduce the severity and mortality associated with the disease.\r\n\r\nChloramphenicol eye ointment could be used for bacterial conjunctivitis, but it does not treat the underlying measles infection.\r\nNystatin oral drops are used to treat oral thrush (a fungal infection), which could be a secondary issue in this case, but it's not the primary treatment for measles.\r\nOral antibiotics are reserved for secondary bacterial complications of measles, such as bacterial pneumonia or otitis media, which are not evident in this case.\r\nParacetamol syrup can be used to reduce fever and provide symptomatic relief but does not alter the course of measles.","reference":"Ralston SH, Penman ID, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP, eds. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 23rd ed. Elsevier; 2018: 236.","responses":[{"text":"Nystatin oral drops","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloramphenicol eye ointment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral vitamin A","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Paracetamol syrup","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral antibiotic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12426,"text":"A 23-year-old medical student develops nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, and diarrhea after eating street food. Her complete blood count shows hemoglobin 12.8 g/dL, white blood cells 4200/mm³, erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) 35 mm/h, and low platelet count (98000/μL). What is the most predominant feature of this condition?","explanation":"This presentation is indicative of a bacterial gastrointestinal infection, possibly caused by pathogens such as Shigella, or certain strains of Escherichia coli, which are known to cause **bloody diarrhea.**\r\n\r\nThese bacteria often contaminate food and water, leading to foodborne illnesses characterized by gastrointestinal symptoms. Bloody diarrhea suggests that the infection is causing inflammation and damage to the gastrointestinal mucosa. The low platelet count could be a secondary effect of the infection, such as certain enterohemorrhagic strains of E. coli (i.e., those with\r\nthe O157:H7 serotype) (Shiga toxin–producing E. coli [STEC]) \r\n\r\nChronic carrier state is possible with certain infections such as typhoid, but it's not the predominant acute presentation.\r\nRose red spots on the abdomen are characteristic of typhoid fever caused by Salmonella typhi.\r\nPetechiae on the arms and legs can be seen in various conditions, including viral hemorrhagic fevers or other systemic infections, but are not a predominant feature in typical cases of foodborne gastrointestinal infections.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 148.","responses":[{"text":"Patient can present with bloody diarrhea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient can present with rose red spots","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Disease can be transmitted by contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient has petechia on the arms and legs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Can result in a chronic carrier state","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12427,"text":"A 45-year-old male is suffering from high-grade fever, severe body ache, and bleeding from the nose and mouth since the last 2 days. He consulted his general physician but the prescribed medicines did not give any relief. He works as a butcher and handles alive animals. His complete blood count shows hemoglobin 14.5 g/dL, white blood cells 1200/mm³, platelet count 37000/mm³. What is the best treatment option for him?","explanation":"Given the patient's clinical picture, a hemorrhagic fever such as a viral hemorrhagic fever should be considered. The best immediate treatment option for him is **IV antibiotics to prevent bacterial infection**.\r\n\r\nIn cases of viral hemorrhagic fever, where specific antiviral treatments may not be available or the exact viral etiology is unknown, supportive care is critical. This includes maintaining hydration and electrolyte balance (IV normal saline), managing fever and pain (IV paracetamol), and importantly, preventing secondary bacterial infections, which can be life-threatening, especially in the context of a compromised immune system (hence IV antibiotics).\r\n\r\nWhile transfusion of platelets might be considered due to thrombocytopenia, it is usually reserved for cases where there is significant bleeding or the platelet count is critically low. The use of IV domperidone or prokinetic agents is not indicated in this scenario unless there are specific gastrointestinal symptoms that require such treatment.","reference":"Antibiotics - uses. nhs.uk. Published October 20, 2017. Accessed November 13, 2022. https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/antibiotics/uses/","responses":[{"text":"Transfusion of platelet mega units","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV domperidone or any other prokinetic agent","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV normal saline","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV paracetamol as per need","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"IV antibiotics to prevent bacterial infection","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12428,"text":"A 45-year-old female had fever and chills. Malarial parasite was positive on MP-ICT. She was treated with artemisinin based combination therapy. She went to donate blood after one session. The blood bank refused donation because she had gametocytes on peripheral smear. She is worried and wants a retreatment. What should be the next step of management?","explanation":"ACTs are effective in reducing the asexual and sexual stages (gametocytes) of the malaria parasite, thereby decreasing the parasite burden significantly. The presence of gametocytes post-treatment indicates that the initial course of ACT might not have completely cleared the infection or that there was a recrudescence. Therefore, **repeating the course of ACT** is appropriate to ensure the complete eradication of the parasite, including the gametocytes.","reference":"Nosten F, White NJ. Artemisinin-Based Combination Treatment of Falciparum Malaria. American Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene; 2007. Accessed January 20, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1713/","responses":[{"text":"Needs long term prophylaxis to clear the gametocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A different antimalarial drug should be used","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No need for treatment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Repeat course of artemisinin based combination therapy (ACT)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Repeat peripheral smear from well reputed laboratory","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15409,"text":"Which of the following is a complication of Entamoeba histolytica?","explanation":"*Entamoeba histolytica* is a protozoan parasite responsible for causing a disease known as amebiasis. \r\n**Amebic abscess** occurs when the parasite invades the liver and forms an abscess, a localized collection of pus. This can result in symptoms such as right upper abdominal pain, fever, and hepatomegaly (enlarged liver). If left untreated, the abscess can rupture, leading to life-threatening complications like peritonitis or pleuropulmonary involvement.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 330.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cysticercosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydatid cyst disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amebic abscess","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15410,"text":"A medical worker accidentally gets pricked by a needle used on an HIV-positive patient. What is the risk percentage of him getting an HIV infection?","explanation":"The risk percentage of a medical worker contracting HIV after a needlestick injury from an HIV-positive patient is approximately **0.3%**.\r\n\r\nThis risk is not uniform and depends on various factors, including the viral load of the patient, the depth of the needlestick, and the use of post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP). Studies have estimated the average risk to be around 0.3%. However, this risk can be reduced significantly if the medical worker seeks immediate medical attention, receives appropriate PEP, and follows the prescribed regimen diligently.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 352.","responses":[{"text":"0.1%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.3%","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"0.05%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.5%","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"0.67%","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15411,"text":"A man falls in the washroom and later presents with a high-grade fever. The doctor suspects that he has chronic inflammation. Which of the following are the dominant cells of chronic inflammation?","explanation":"The dominant cells of chronic inflammation are **macrophages**. Chronic inflammation is characterized by a prolonged and sustained immune response to tissue injury or infection. In this process, **macrophages** play a central role by phagocytosing pathogens, cellular debris, and foreign substances. They also release various cytokines and growth factors that contribute to tissue repair and remodeling.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 97.","responses":[{"text":"Macrophages","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15412,"text":"Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) has structural genes and functional genes. Which of the following is a structural gene in HIV?","explanation":"Structural genes in HIV are responsible for encoding the viral proteins that make up the structure of the virus itself. These genes are essential for the replication and assembly of the virus.\r\n\r\nThe **pol** gene codes for the viral enzymes, including reverse transcriptase, integrase, and protease, which are critical for the various stages of the viral life cycle. Reverse transcriptase is involved in the conversion of the viral RNA genome into DNA, integrase facilitates the integration of the viral DNA into the host genome, and protease is essential for the maturation and assembly of new viral particles.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 367.","responses":[{"text":"pol","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"vif","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"rev","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"tat","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"nef","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15531,"text":"Penicillin should not be administered via which of the following routes?","explanation":"The **intrathecal route** involves the injection of medications directly into the spinal canal or cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) for specific medical purposes. The central nervous system (CNS) is highly sensitive to certain substances, and penicillin is one of them. Administering penicillin intrathecally can result in neurologic complications such as seizures, encephalopathy, and other serious adverse effects.","reference":"Dow Lecture slides: Infectious module, Pharmacology slides, Topic: Cell wall synthesis inhibitors.","responses":[{"text":"Intravenous route","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intraperitoneal route","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intra-articular route","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrathecal route","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramuscular route","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15532,"text":"Which of the following is a non-infectious cause of vaginal discharge?","explanation":"Vaginal discharge can have various causes, and one of them is exposure to **chemical irritants**. These irritants can disrupt the natural pH and balance of the vaginal environment. Common chemical irritants include douches, scented soaps, bubble baths, and certain topical contraceptives. When these substances come into contact with the vaginal area, they can lead to irritation and an increase in vaginal discharge. This type of discharge is usually clear or white and may be accompanied by itching or burning sensations. \r\n\r\nIn contrast, there are infectious causes of vaginal discharge, such as *Chlamydia trachomatis* and *Trichomonas vaginalis*. *Chlamydia trachomatis* is a bacterium responsible for a sexually transmitted infection, while *Trichomonas vaginalis* is a protozoan parasite that causes trichomoniasis, another sexually transmitted infection. Both of these infections can result in abnormal vaginal discharge along with other symptoms. Another infectious cause is *Candida albicans*, which leads to yeast infections. Yeast infections typically produce a thick, white, cottage cheese-like discharge and are also associated with itching and irritation.","reference":"Sim M, Logan S, Goh LH. Vaginal discharge: evaluation and management in primary care. Singapore Medical Journal. Published June 2020. Accessed April 1, 2023. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7905126/","responses":[{"text":"Chemical irritants","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Candida albicans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomonas vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15533,"text":"Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is used to treat which of the following infections in HIV-positive patients?","explanation":"**Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP)**  is an opportunistic fungal infection that commonly affects individuals with weakened immune systems, particularly HIV-positive patients. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, often abbreviated as TMP-SMX, is the first-line treatment and prophylaxis for PCP in these patients. It effectively targets the causative agent, Pneumocystis jirovecii, helping to clear the infection and prevent its recurrence.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 359.","responses":[{"text":"Oral candidiasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Crytoccocal meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Toxoplasmosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15534,"text":"A medical officer detects an HIV (human immunodeficiency virus) positive case in the blood bank and searches for the sexual partner of the donor to prevent and treat the disease in the partner. Which process is described here?","explanation":"**HIV contact tracing** is a public health strategy aimed at identifying and notifying individuals who may have been exposed to the HIV virus through sexual contact or other means with an HIV-positive individual. In this scenario, the medical officer is proactively seeking out the sexual partner of the HIV-positive blood donor to inform them of potential exposure and offer HIV testing, counseling, and appropriate medical care.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Community-medicine, Topic: Prevention and control of AIDS and STDs.","responses":[{"text":"HIV contact tracing","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV screening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV prophylaxis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV primary prevention","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV case detection","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15535,"text":"A person, while traveling, carries a disease with him from an area where it is highly prevalent, to a place in which it does not normally occur. Which of the following terms is used for it?","explanation":"When an individual travels from an area with a high prevalence of a particular disease to a new location where that disease is not typically found, they are introducing an **\"exotic\"** disease to the new area. This can potentially lead to outbreaks or localized transmission in the new region, as the local population may not have pre-existing immunity or effective public health measures in place to control the disease.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Community-medicine, Topic: Epidemiology of infectious disease.","responses":[{"text":"Hyper epidemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pandemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endemic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Exotic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Holo endemic","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15536,"text":"A young female presents to the outpatient department with greenish, foul-smelling vaginal discharge. A wet mount shows pear-shaped trophozoites with a jerky motion. Which of the following is the most likely organism involved?","explanation":"**Trichomoniasis,** caused by the protozoan parasite *Trichomonas vaginalis,* is a sexually transmitted infection (STI) that often presents with greenish, frothy, and malodorous vaginal discharge. The pear-shaped trophozoites of *Trichomonas vaginalis* can be observed in wet mounts from vaginal swabs and are known for their characteristic jerky or whip-like motion under the microscope.\r\n\r\n*Chlamydia trachomatis* and *Neisseria gonorrhoeae* are bacterial pathogens that can also cause vaginal discharge but typically present differently and require different diagnostic methods for confirmation.\r\n*Entamoeba histolytica* is a protozoan responsible for causing amebiasis, which primarily affects the intestines, leading to diarrhea and abdominal pain. It is not associated with vaginal discharge.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 418-419.","responses":[{"text":"Entamaoeba histolytica","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomonas vaginalis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15537,"text":"In an AIDS (acquired immune deficiency syndrome) patient, purplish, non-blanching nodules appear in the lower extremities. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Kaposi's sarcoma** is a cancer caused by the human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8) and is more commonly seen in individuals with compromised immune systems, such as AIDS patients. It typically presents as purplish or reddish-brown lesions or nodules on the skin and mucous membranes. These lesions are often non-blanching, meaning they do not fade when pressure is applied.\r\n\r\n**Bacillary angiomatosis** can also cause skin lesions but is usually more papular and may be red or violaceous. It is caused by bacteria, Bartonella species, and can occur in immunocompromised individuals.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 358.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Molluscum contagiosum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacillary angiomatosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Kaposi's sarcoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyogenic granulomas","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15538,"text":"A patient starts having diarrhea after taking antibiotics during his hospital stay. Which organism is most likely involved?","explanation":"The most likely organism involved in a patient who develops diarrhea after taking antibiotics during a hospital stay is:\r\n***Clostridium difficile***, commonly referred to as C. diff, is a bacterium that can cause symptoms ranging from diarrhea to life-threatening inflammation of the colon. It is often associated with antibiotic use, particularly in **hospitalized patients**, as antibiotics can disrupt the normal gut flora, allowing for C. difficile overgrowth and resulting in disease. This condition is often referred to as ***Clostridium difficile***-**associated diarrhea (CDAD)** or ***C. difficile*** **infection (CDI)**. The management of the condition may involve discontinuation of the offending antibiotic and initiation of specific antibiotic therapy against C. difficile.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 136.","responses":[{"text":"Clostridium perfringens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium botulinum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium tetani","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clostridium difficile","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15547,"text":"Which of the following organisms can cause cervical cancer and anogenital warts known as condylomata acuminata?","explanation":null,"reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 295.","responses":[{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human papilloma virus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15548,"text":"Which of the following infections in sexually active women does not cause vaginal discharge?","explanation":"**HIV** is primarily a bloodborne and sexually transmitted virus that targets the immune system. It doesn't directly cause vaginal discharge, as it primarily infects immune cells in the body. While some women with advanced HIV infection may experience various gynecological symptoms or infections as a result of their compromised immune systems, vaginal discharge is not a hallmark symptom or direct consequence of HIV itself.\r\n\r\n**Trichomoniasis** is a sexually transmitted infection caused by a parasite and is known to cause a frothy, malodorous vaginal discharge.\r\n**Bacterial vaginosis** is a common vaginal infection characterized by a fishy-smelling, grayish-white vaginal discharge.\r\n**Chlamydia** is a bacterial sexually transmitted infection that can lead to vaginal discharge among other symptoms.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 374.","responses":[{"text":"Chlamydia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV (human immunodeficiency virus)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Streptococcal/staphylococcal infections","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomoniasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial vaginosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15549,"text":"A patient presents to the outpatient department with abdominal pain, relative bradycardia, and a fever that started as low-grade but has been persistently increasing for days. He also has salmon-colored spots on his trunk. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Typhoid fever** is a bacterial infection caused by *Salmonella enterica* serotype Typhi. It is characterized by a gradual onset of fever, which starts low-grade and increases over time. Abdominal pain and other gastrointestinal symptoms are common, and relative bradycardia (a slower-than-expected heart rate given the high fever) is a classic clinical finding.\r\n\r\nThe salmon-colored spots, also known as **rose spots**, can appear on the trunk and abdomen and are a characteristic feature of typhoid fever.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 308.","responses":[{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dengue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Roseola","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15550,"text":"A patient presents to the clinic with a high-grade fever, productive cough, and a runny nose with red eyes. He, later on, notices a maculopapular rash beginning to appear on his forehead. What is the patient most likely suffering from?","explanation":"**Measles,** also known as rubeola, is a highly contagious viral infection caused by the measles virus. The initial symptoms often include a high fever, cough, runny nose, and red, watery eyes. This is followed by the characteristic rash, which typically starts on the face and spreads to other parts of the body.\r\n\r\n**Roseola**, on the other hand, typically presents with a high fever in the initial stage, which is then followed by a characteristic rash once the fever subsides.\r\n\r\n**Rubella** (German measles) can also cause a rash, but it is usually a mild illness compared to measles and is known for its association with birth defects if contracted during pregnancy.\r\n\r\n**Chickenpox** (varicella) presents with an itchy rash that usually starts on the trunk and spreads to other areas.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 312.","responses":[{"text":"Chicken pox","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Roseola","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15551,"text":"A child is brought to the clinic for having loose stools with a frequency of 20 per day. On examination, normal skin turgor and no sunken eyes are found. When water is offered, he drinks it eagerly. What is the classification according to IMNCI?","explanation":"The child's presentation aligns with the classification of **diarrhea with no dehydration** according to the IMNCI guidelines. \r\nThis classification is based on several clinical signs that indicate the child's hydration status. Firstly, the child exhibits normal skin turgor, indicating that they are adequately hydrated. Skin turgor is a measure of skin elasticity, and normal turgor is a positive sign. Additionally, the absence of sunken eyes in the child's examination is another indicator that severe dehydration is not present.  Furthermore, the child's eagerness to drink water is a positive sign, suggesting a desire for rehydration.","reference":"WHO, UNICEF. Integrated Management Of Neonatal \u0026 Childhood Illness. 2nd ed. Ministry of National Health Services; 2019: 6.","responses":[{"text":"Diarrhea with some dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea with mild dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea with no dehydration","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea with moderate dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diarrhea with severe dehydration","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15552,"text":"What is the term used for diarrhea (with or without blood in stool) that starts acutely and occurs for at least 14 days?","explanation":"**Persistent diarrhea** is characterized by the prolonged duration of diarrhea symptoms, which differentiates it from acute diarrhea, where symptoms typically resolve in less than 14 days. In cases of persistent diarrhea, the symptoms continue for two weeks but not more than a month.\r\n\r\nIt's important to note that dysentery typically refers to diarrhea with blood or mucus in the stool, often caused by infectious agents like Shigella or Amebiasis. On the other hand, chronic diarrhea usually denotes a more long-term condition lasting for more than a month.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Medicine, Topic: Approach to an adult patient with infectious diarrhea and dysentry.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dysentry","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute diarrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Persistent diarrhea","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic diarrhea","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15553,"text":"Which of the following stages of the malarial parasite is liberated after the rupture of erythrocytes?","explanation":"**Merozoites** are the form of the malaria parasite that invades and infects new red blood cells, continuing the cycle of infection. The rupture of infected red blood cells allows merozoites to be released, and they then go on to invade fresh erythrocytes, leading to the cycle of replication and the ongoing destruction of red blood cells, which is a hallmark of malaria infection.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 421.","responses":[{"text":"Schizonts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gametocyte","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Merozoites","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophozoite","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sporozoites","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15564,"text":"A person having mucopurulent urethral discharge is diagnosed with gonorrhea. Which of the following will be shown on culture?","explanation":"Gonorrhea is caused by the bacterium *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, and one of its characteristic features is that it appears as **Gram-negative diplococci** under microscopic examination. This means that when the urethral discharge is cultured and analyzed in the laboratory, the bacteria responsible for the infection will appear as pairs of cocci (round-shaped bacteria) that do not retain the crystal violet stain (Gram-negative). These diplococci can often be observed within white blood cells, contributing to the mucopurulent nature of the discharge.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 129.","responses":[{"text":"Gram negative cocci in grape like cluster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive cocci","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram negative diplococci","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive cocci in grape like cluster","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram positive rods","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15565,"text":"A child is brought to the pediatrics clinic for evaluation of diarrhea. His systemic findings are unremarkable except that he has less weight and height for his age. It is found that he has malabsorption syndrome. What is the causative agent in this case?","explanation":"*Giardia lamblia* is a protozoan parasite that commonly infects the small intestine in humans. It is a well-known cause of malabsorption syndrome in children, leading to poor weight and height gain for their age. The parasite attaches to the lining of the small intestine and impairs the absorption of nutrients, which results in diarrhea, malnutrition, and growth stunting.\r\n\r\nPatients infected with Giardia typically present with symptoms such as diarrhea, abdominal pain, bloating, and weight loss. The infection is often associated with contaminated water sources.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018 414-415.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterobius vermicularis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giardia lamblia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptosporidium hominis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15566,"text":"A patient presents to the clinic with a complaint of bloody diarrhea. A sorbitol-negative strain of Escherichia coli is found to be the causative agent. Which of the following has caused this condition?","explanation":"**Enterohemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC)** is a pathogenic strain of Escherichia coli that is known for causing bloody diarrhea. It is characterized by its ability to produce a toxin called Shiga toxin, which can lead to severe gastrointestinal symptoms, including bloody stools. EHEC is a significant public health concern as it can result in outbreaks and foodborne illnesses, often associated with the consumption of contaminated food, such as undercooked ground beef, raw milk, and unpasteurized juices.\r\n\r\nThe Shiga toxin produced by EHEC can cause damage to the lining of the intestines, leading to the release of blood into the stool. This condition can sometimes progress to more severe complications, such as hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS), which can affect the kidneys and be life-threatening.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 149.","responses":[{"text":"Enteroaggregative E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterotoxigenic E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enteroinvasive E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Enterohemorrhagic E. coli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Enteropathogenic E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15569,"text":"A person presents to the clinic with bloody diarrhea and is diagnosed with intestinal amebiasis caused by Entamoeba histolytica. Which of the following is true for this organism?","explanation":"*Entamoeba histolytica* is a protozoan parasite responsible for intestinal amebiasis, a condition characterized by symptoms like bloody diarrhea, abdominal pain, and fever. Trophozoites are the active, motile form of this parasite that exist within the host's intestines. One of the distinguishing features of E. histolytica **trophozoites is their ability to ingest red blood cells** (RBCs), which can be observed in stool samples. This phenomenon is often referred to as erythrophagocytosis.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 411-412.","responses":[{"text":"Trophozoites have three nuclei","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophozoites contain ingested RBCs","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophozoites have chromatin granules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophozoites contain marginated nucleolus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15570,"text":"An 18-year-old man is having conjunctival erythema with lacrimation and purulent discharge more prominent in the left eye. He consults his ophthalmologist who tells him that he is having follicular conjunctivitis and punctate keratitis. Giemsa stain shows cytoplasmic inclusions with no growth on culture with Gram stain. What is the most likely cause?","explanation":"*Chlamydia trachomatis* is an obligate intracellular bacterium responsible for various clinical syndromes, including ocular infections. The presentation described, with follicular conjunctivitis and punctate keratitis, is characteristic of **trachoma**, which is caused by specific serovars of Chlamydia trachomatis. Trachoma is a leading cause of infectious blindness worldwide.\r\n\r\nThe Giemsa stain showing cytoplasmic inclusions, along with the negative culture for bacterial growth, is consistent with the diagnosis. These inclusions are known as **intracytoplasmic** or **cytoplasmic** inclusions, which are characteristic of chlamydial infections.","reference":"(1) Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 203.\r\n  \r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 319.","responses":[{"text":"Candida albicans","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Treponema pallidum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neisseria gonorrhoeae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human papillomavirus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15571,"text":"Which of the following is used for the treatment of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus?","explanation":"MRSA is a strain of *Staphylococcus aureus* that has become resistant to many antibiotics, including methicillin and other beta-lactam antibiotics like penicillin and ceftriaxone. Therefore, traditional antibiotics like penicillin G and ceftriaxone are ineffective against MRSA.\r\n\r\n**Vancomycin,** on the other hand, is a glycopeptide antibiotic that remains effective against MRSA. It works by inhibiting cell wall synthesis in bacteria, including MRSA, which ultimately leads to cell death.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 378.","responses":[{"text":"Vancomycin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nafcillin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin G","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythromycin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15572,"text":"Which of the following drugs is a protease inhibitor?","explanation":"Protease inhibitors (PIs) are a class of antiretroviral drugs used in the treatment of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus) infection. These drugs work by inhibiting the activity of the HIV protease enzyme, which plays a crucial role in the final stages of viral replication. HIV protease cleaves long chains of viral proteins into smaller functional units, allowing the virus to mature and become infectious. By inhibiting this enzyme, protease inhibitors prevent the formation of mature, infectious HIV particles.\r\n\r\n**Indinavir,** along with other protease inhibitors like ritonavir, saquinavir, and lopinavir, has been used as part of highly active antiretroviral therapy (HAART) regimens to suppress HIV replication and slow down disease progression in HIV-infected individuals.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 267.","responses":[{"text":"Raltegravir","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stavudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Zidovudine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indinavir","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tenofovir","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15574,"text":"A child presents with high-grade fever, runny nose, and cough. White lesions are found on the oral mucosa. What is the pathognomonic sign for measles?","explanation":"Measles, caused by the measles virus (a paramyxovirus), typically presents with a characteristic set of clinical features. One of the hallmark signs of measles is the presence of **Koplik's spots.** These are small, white, or bluish-white spots that appear on the mucous membranes of the mouth, particularly on the buccal mucosa (inner lining of the cheeks) and the opposite surfaces of the molars. Koplik's spots are usually one of the earliest signs of measles and can precede the rash.\r\n\r\nIn addition to Koplik's spots, individuals with measles often develop a high-grade fever, runny nose (coryza), cough, and a characteristic red rash that starts on the face and spreads to the rest of the body.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 279.","responses":[{"text":"Koplik’s spots","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Erythema nodosum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vesicular lesions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Red spots","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Umbilicated lesions","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15577,"text":"A 28-year-old man has a fever, headache, and a rash present on his trunk and extremities with itching. On examinations, vesicles and papules of varying sizes are seen on his trunk and extremities and some are in the healing stage. What is the likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Chickenpox,** also known as Varicella, is a highly contagious viral infection caused by the Varicella-Zoster virus. It typically presents with symptoms such as fever, headache, and a characteristic rash. In this scenario, the patient's symptoms match those of chickenpox. The key clinical features that point towards this diagnosis are the presence of a fever, headache, and a rash with vesicles and papules of varying sizes on the trunk and extremities, some of which are in the healing stage. \r\n\r\nChickenpox is known for its **itchy rash** and the appearance of lesions at different stages of development, including vesicles, papules, and crusted lesions. It is a **classic childhood disease** but can occur in adults as well, which is evident in this 28-year-old man.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 282.","responses":[{"text":"Chicken pox","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Roseola","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small pox","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mumps","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15586,"text":"A woman is admitted for an elective/non-emergency procedure. Which type of consent should be taken before the operation?","explanation":"For an elective/non-emergency medical procedure, the appropriate type of consent to be obtained is **expressed and written** consent. Expressed consent, particularly when given in writing, is the gold standard for non-emergency medical procedures. This form of consent ensures that the patient has been informed about the specifics of the procedure, including its risks, benefits, and alternatives, and has agreed to proceed with full understanding.\r\n\r\nWritten consent serves as a documented evidence of the patient's decision-making process and understanding, providing legal protection for both the patient and the healthcare provider. It is crucial in elective procedures where the patient has the time and capacity to understand all relevant information and make an informed decision.\r\n\r\nOral consent may be considered in some situations but lacks the formality and documentation of written consent. Implied consent is typically reserved for emergency scenarios where immediate action is necessary, and the patient is unable to give explicit consent.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Forensic-medicine, Topic: Laws related to medical men II.","responses":[{"text":"Written","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral and expressed","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Implied","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Expressed and written","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15587,"text":"Which of the following statements is true about chloramphenicol?","explanation":"The correct mechanism of action for chloramphenicol is that it **inhibits protein synthesis** by binding to the **50S subunit of ribosomes** in bacterial cells. This action disrupts the formation of peptide bonds during protein synthesis, thereby inhibiting bacterial growth. It is considered **bacteriostatic** rather than **bactericidal**, as it inhibits bacterial growth without directly killing the bacteria.\r\nChloramphenicol is an antibiotic that belongs to the class of drugs known as **broad-spectrum antibiotics**. \r\nChloramphenicol is not used as an antifungal drug.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 394.","responses":[{"text":"It is bactericidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It inhibits the 50S subunit of ribosomes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"It is an antifungal drug","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is a narrow-spectrum antibiotic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15588,"text":"An old man came with slowly progressive hypopigmented skin lesions on the chest and abdomen. He had a previous history of skin lesions that healed spontaneously. He also reported loss of sensation in some regions of his skin and thickened nerves. What stain will be used to visualize the causative organism?","explanation":"The patient's presentation with slowly progressive hypopigmented skin lesions, a history of previous skin lesions that healed spontaneously, loss of sensation in some skin regions, and thickened nerves suggests a possible diagnosis of **leprosy.** Leprosy is caused by the bacterium *Mycobacterium leprae*.\r\n\r\nThe **Ziehl-Neelsen stain,** also known as the acid-fast stain, is used specifically for the detection of mycobacteria, including Mycobacterium leprae. This stain helps identify the bacterium's characteristic acid-fast properties, which means it resists decolorization by acid-alcohol and retains the stain. Acid-fast staining is essential for the diagnosis of leprosy.","reference":"(1) Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 184.\r\n\r\n(2) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 315.","responses":[{"text":"Gram stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wright stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ziehl Neelsen stain","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Giemsa stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15589,"text":"A patient comes to the emergency department with a history of prolonged cough, fever, and chest infection. He is diagnosed with a case of tuberculosis after getting confirmation from the report of the biopsy. What is tuberculosis characterized by?","explanation":"Tuberculosis often leads to the formation of granulomas in affected tissues. Within these granulomas, a specific type of necrosis called **caseous necrosis** is a hallmark feature. Caseous necrosis appears as a cheese-like, friable material within the granulomas. This necrotic tissue is a result of the body's attempt to contain and wall off the tuberculosis infection.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 178.","responses":[{"text":"Collection of serous fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocyte infiltration","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Congested blood vessels","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Accumulation of neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Caseous necrosis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15590,"text":"A blood culture shows the growth of non-lactose fermenting (colorless), gram-negative bacteria on MacConkey's agar and the production of hydrogen sulfide gas on TSI agar. Which of the following is the most likely organism?","explanation":"*Salmonella typhi* is known for its ability to produce hydrogen sulfide gas, which gives a characteristic black color on TSI agar. Additionally, it is a non-lactose fermenter, appearing colorless on MacConkey's agar. This combination of features is consistent with the findings described.\r\n\r\n*Vibrio cholerae* and *Shigella* are not typically associated with hydrogen sulfide gas production. *Escherichia coli* is a lactose fermenter and would not be colorless on MacConkey's agar.","reference":"Levinson, Warren, et al. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2018: 151.","responses":[{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella typhi","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vibrio cholerae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15592,"text":"A 35-year-old male presents to the clinic with hypopigmented lesions on his limbs and back. He has been treated with antifungals but did not heal. He has also developed polyarthritis with edema. He has thick cutaneous nerves, radial, ulnar, and tibial nerves. The nerves are painful and tender. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Lepromatous leprosy** is a form of leprosy caused by the bacterium *Mycobacterium leprae*. It is characterized by a more severe and widespread involvement of the skin and nerves compared to other forms of leprosy. \r\n\r\nThe patient's presentation of hypopigmented lesions on limbs and back, along with the failure to heal with antifungal treatment, is suggestive of skin involvement typical of lepromatous leprosy. Additionally, the presence of polyarthritis with edema and thick cutaneous nerves is consistent with the neurological and musculoskeletal manifestations seen in this form of leprosy. The painful and tender nerves are indicative of neuritis, which is common in lepromatous leprosy.\r\n\r\nTuberculoid leprosy typically presents with fewer skin lesions and less systemic involvement, while borderline forms exhibit intermediate clinical features.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 314-316.","responses":[{"text":"Borderline tuberculoid leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lepromatous leprosy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculoid leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Borderline lepromatous leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15593,"text":"A patient had a hypopigmented skin lesion on one side, which progressed to multiple sites. Some of these lesions resolved on their own and then new lesions appeared. He also has anorexia, fever, and weight loss. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Borderline tuberculoid leprosy** is a form of leprosy caused by the bacterium *Mycobacterium leprae*. It is characterized by its intermediate clinical features between the more severe lepromatous leprosy and the milder tuberculoid leprosy.\r\n\r\nThe patient's presentation of initially having a single hypopigmented skin lesion that progressed to multiple sites, with some lesions spontaneously resolving and new lesions appearing, is consistent with the evolving nature of borderline tuberculoid leprosy. This form of leprosy often presents with a single skin lesion initially, which may become multiple over time. The anorexia, fever, and weight loss are systemic symptoms that can occur in borderline tuberculoid leprosy.\r\n\r\nLepromatous leprosy typically presents with more severe skin involvement and is unlikely to have the initial presentation described. Tuberculoid leprosy would have fewer lesions, and mid-line leprosy is not a recognized form of leprosy.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 314-316.","responses":[{"text":"Borderline tuberculoid leprosy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculoid leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Borderline lepromatous leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lepromatous leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mid-line leprosy","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15594,"text":"A female patient presents to the clinic with a complaint of purulent vaginal discharge. Gram staining of the discharge reveals gram-negative diplococci. What is the best treatment?","explanation":"The presence of gram-negative diplococci in vaginal discharge is highly suggestive of an infection with *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, the bacterium responsible for gonorrhea. \r\n\r\n**Ceftriaxone** is the recommended first-line treatment for gonorrhea according to guidelines from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). It is administered as a single intramuscular injection. This antibiotic is effective against Neisseria gonorrhoeae and is preferred due to the increasing antibiotic resistance seen in this bacterium.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 128-129.","responses":[{"text":"Ceftriaxone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Azithromycin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciprofloxacin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penicillin G","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amoxicillin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15595,"text":"A 35-year-old diabetic patient presents to the outpatient department with complaints of fever associated with rigors and chills, and increased frequency of urine. She also complains of pain during micturition. Other systemic findings are unremarkable. What is the most accurate test for diagnosis?","explanation":"This clinical presentation, with fever, rigors, chills, and urinary symptoms, is suggestive of a **urinary tract infection (UTI)**. UTIs are common in diabetic patients due to factors such as elevated blood sugar levels that can promote bacterial growth in the urinary tract.\r\n\r\nTo confirm the diagnosis of a UTI and identify the specific causative organism, a **urine dipstick test (Urine DR)** followed by a **urine culture** is the most accurate approach. The urine dipstick test can provide preliminary information about the presence of white blood cells and nitrites, which are indicative of a UTI. However, a urine culture is required to isolate and identify the bacteria causing the infection and determine their antibiotic susceptibility.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 600.","responses":[{"text":"Complete blood count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urine DR/culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malarial antigen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ultrasound","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15596,"text":"A patient presents to the clinic with complaints of cough and chest pain suggestive of pneumonia. He has had a splenectomy. Which of the following gram-positive organisms can be the causative agent?","explanation":"In a patient with a history of splenectomy presenting with symptoms suggestive of pneumonia, the most likely causative gram-positive organism is **Pneumococcus** (*Streptococcus pneumoniae*). Individuals who have undergone splenectomy are at increased risk of infections, particularly from encapsulated bacteria like *Streptococcus pneumoniae*.\r\n\r\nThe spleen plays a crucial role in filtering blood and mounting an immune response against encapsulated bacteria. Splenectomy, or surgical removal of the spleen, impairs the body's ability to clear these bacteria effectively, leading to an increased susceptibility to infections from these organisms.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 629.","responses":[{"text":"Pseudomonas","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumococcus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasmodium falciparum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15597,"text":"Which of the following organisms is commonly responsible for causing watery diarrhea in less than 5-year-olds and results in more than 2 million hospital admissions annually?","explanation":"**Rotavirus** is a highly contagious virus that primarily affects infants and young children. It is a leading cause of severe diarrhea, particularly in children aged 2 and under. The virus is transmitted through the fecal-oral route and can lead to acute gastroenteritis with symptoms such as watery diarrhea, vomiting, fever, and abdominal pain.\r\n\r\nRotavirus is responsible for a significant global burden of diarrheal diseases in young children, leading to millions of hospital admissions each year, especially in developing countries where access to clean water and healthcare resources may be limited.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 292.","responses":[{"text":"Shigella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rotavirus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entamoeba histolytica","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15598,"text":"A man presents to the clinic with the complaint of a thick, yellow, mucoid, and purulent urethral discharge. He has had a new sexual partner for two weeks. Which infections would you consider in this patient?","explanation":"This clinical presentation is highly suggestive of a sexually transmitted infection (STI) affecting the genitourinary tract. Both **Gonorrhea and Chlamydia** can cause urethral discharge with these characteristics.\r\n\r\nGonorrhea, caused by the bacterium *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, typically presents with purulent urethral discharge, and it is known for its mucoid and thick appearance. Chlamydia, caused by *Chlamydia trachomatis*, can also cause similar symptoms, including urethral discharge.\r\n\r\nTrichomoniasis, caused by the protozoan **Trichomonas vaginalis**, can also result in urethral discharge, but it is usually more frothy and greenish-yellow, which does not match the thick, yellow, mucoid, and purulent description provided by the patient.","reference":"Leonard, Cory Ann, et al. “Pathogenic Interplay Between Chlamydia Trachomatis and Neisseria Gonorrhoeae That Influences Management and Control Efforts—More Questions than Answers?” Current Clinical Microbiology Reports, vol. 6, no. 3, Sept. 2019, pp. 182–91. Springer Link, https://doi.org/10.1007/s40588-019-00125-4.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonorrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonorrhea and Chlamydia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomoniasis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15599,"text":"A patient is brought to the clinic with the complaint of fever, cough, dyspnea, and cyanosis. He also has tachycardia and his blood pressure is 80/60 mmHg. On auscultation, crackles and decreased breath sounds can be heard in the right lower lobe. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Medicine, Topic: Sepsis and SIRS.","responses":[{"text":"Systemic infammatory response syndrome (SIRS)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Severe sepsis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Multiple organ dysfunction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sepsis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15600,"text":"The coagulation cascade in systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS) is mediated by which of the following?","explanation":"SIRS is a complex condition characterized by a dysregulated inflammatory response to various insults, such as infection, trauma, or other inflammatory conditions. This dysregulation can lead to the activation of various pathways, including the coagulation cascade.\r\n\r\n**Tissue factor (TF),** also known as thromboplastin, is a cell membrane protein that plays a central role in initiating the extrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade. When exposed to blood, as can occur during tissue injury or inflammation, TF binds with factor VIIa to activate the coagulation pathway, ultimately leading to the formation of blood clots.","reference":"Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 199.","responses":[{"text":"IL1 and IL6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tumor necrosis factor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tissue factor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"C5a","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15601,"text":"Which of the following cells are found in the synovium of the joint in case of acute arthritis?","explanation":"Acute arthritis is characterized by a sudden onset of joint inflammation, leading to symptoms such as pain, swelling, and loss of joint function. **Neutrophils** are the hallmark of acute inflammation and are the first immune cells to migrate to the site of infection or injury, including joints affected by acute arthritis. They play a crucial role in phagocytosing pathogens and releasing inflammatory mediators to combat the inflammatory insult.\r\n\r\nBasophils are more associated with allergic responses, while eosinophils are often seen in conditions involving allergies and parasitic infections.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1205.","responses":[{"text":"Basophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dendritic cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Eosinophils","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15602,"text":"Which of the following leads to the dilation of the arterioles and increased venous permeability?","explanation":"**Histamine** is a potent inflammatory mediator released by various cells, including mast cells and basophils, in response to allergens, injury, or immune activation. When histamine is released, it binds to histamine receptors on the endothelial cells lining blood vessels.\r\n\r\nHistamine binds to H1 receptors on endothelial cells, leading to the relaxation and dilation of arterioles. This results in increased blood flow to the affected area, contributing to the characteristic redness and warmth seen in inflammation.\r\n\r\nHistamine also binds to H1 receptors on venule endothelial cells, causing gaps between endothelial cells to widen. This increased permeability allows fluids and inflammatory cells, including neutrophils, to move from the bloodstream into the surrounding tissues, resulting in swelling and edema.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 85-86, 88.","responses":[{"text":"Histamine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotriene B4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Steroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15604,"text":"A 40-year-old male presents with dyspnea, cyanosis, and tachycardia. He is a chain smoker and there is a ventilation-perfusion mismatch on the V/Q scan. Which of the following lung complications can result as a result of systemic inflammatory response syndrome (SIRS)?","explanation":"**ARDS** is a severe and life-threatening condition characterized by diffuse inflammation in the lungs, leading to impaired gas exchange and severe respiratory distress. It can result from various systemic insults, including infections, trauma, and SIRS. In SIRS, the systemic inflammatory response can lead to lung injury and the development of ARDS.\r\n\r\nChronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD) and lung cancer are typically associated with chronic exposure to smoking and are not directly related to SIRS. Lung infection, while capable of causing respiratory distress, is not a complication of SIRS in the same way that ARDS is.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Medicine, Topic: Sepsis and SIRS.","responses":[{"text":"Lung infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung cancer","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15605,"text":"Which of the following statements about interferon-α is incorrect?","explanation":"**Lamivudine** is an antiviral medication that is used to treat hepatitis B, but it **does not interfere with the activity of interferon-α** against hepatitis B. In fact, lamivudine and interferon-α can be used together in the treatment of chronic hepatitis B, as they have different mechanisms of action.\r\n\r\nAt the start of treatment with interferon-α, many patients experience flu-like symptoms, such as fever, chills, headache, and muscle aches.\r\nInterferon-α has been used in the treatment of genital warts, although it is not the first-line treatment for this condition.\r\nToxicity of interferon-α includes bone marrow suppression, which can lead to conditions like anemia, thrombocytopenia, and neutropenia.\r\nInterferon-α is used in the management of hepatitis C, often in combination with other antiviral agents, especially before the development of direct-acting antivirals.","reference":"(1) Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 439.\r\n\r\n(2) Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 884-885, 892.","responses":[{"text":"Toxicity includes bone marrow suppression","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Indications include treatment of genital warts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lamivudine interferes with its activity against hepatitis B","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"At the start of treatment, most patients experience flu like symptoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is used in the management of hepatitis C","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15607,"text":"Which of the following is an important dose-dependent adverse effect of dapsone?","explanation":"Dapsone is an antibiotic commonly used to treat conditions such as leprosy and dermatitis herpetiformis. One of its known side effects is the potential to cause **methemoglobinemia,** a condition in which the iron within hemoglobin is oxidized to its ferric form (Fe3+), rendering hemoglobin unable to bind and transport oxygen effectively. Methemoglobinemia can lead to cyanosis (bluish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes), shortness of breath, and tissue hypoxia.","reference":"(1) Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 850.\r\n\r\n(2) Kurien G, Jamil RT, Preuss CV. Dapsone. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2023. Accessed April 11, 2023. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470552/","responses":[{"text":"Cirrhosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemolysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methemoglobinemia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal failure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15608,"text":"Which of the following is a late complication of measles?","explanation":"**Subacute Sclerosing Panencephalitis (SSPE)** is a rare but severe neurological complication that occurs years after a person has had measles. It is caused by a persistent measles virus infection in the brain. SSPE typically presents with a gradual and progressive decline in neurological function, including behavioral changes, muscle spasms, and intellectual deterioration. It ultimately leads to severe neurological impairment and is often fatal.","reference":"CDC. “Measles Complications.” Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 28 Nov. 2022, https://www.cdc.gov/measles/symptoms/complications.html.","responses":[{"text":"Hepatitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subacute sclerosing panencephalitis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Otitis media","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bacterial pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15609,"text":"A person, before going on a trip to a malaria-endemic area, takes prophylaxis for chloroquine-resistant falciparum malaria but nonetheless develops Plasmodium vivax malaria. Which of the following drugs did he most likely take?","explanation":"**Mefloquine** is an antimalarial medication commonly used for the prevention of chloroquine-resistant Plasmodium falciparum malaria. However, it does not provide effective prophylaxis against Plasmodium vivax.\r\n\r\nMefloquine is effective against the blood stages of Plasmodium falciparum, but it does not target the liver stages of Plasmodium vivax, which are responsible for relapses. This makes it an unsuitable choice for comprehensive malaria prophylaxis in areas where Plasmodium vivax is prevalent.\r\n\r\nProguanil is often used in combination with atovaquone for prophylaxis but may not be as effective against chloroquine-resistant Plasmodium falciparum on its own.\r\nPrimaquine is effective against the liver stages of Plasmodium vivax and is used to prevent relapses but is not typically used solely for prophylaxis against falciparum malaria.\r\nQuinine is used mainly for the treatment rather than prophylaxis of malaria.\r\nAtovaquone, usually in combination with proguanil, is another option for prophylaxis against chloroquine-resistant Plasmodium falciparum.","reference":"Katzung BG, ed. Basic \u0026 Clinical Pharmacology. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 920, 924, 926.","responses":[{"text":"Quinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atovaqoune","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mefloquine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proguanil","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primaquine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15610,"text":"Which of the following antimalarial drugs acts as a blood schizonticide and a sporontocide?","explanation":"**Chloroquine** is a widely used antimalarial medication that is effective against the blood stage of the malaria parasite, known as the schizont stage. It works by interfering with the parasite's ability to break down and digest hemoglobin, ultimately leading to the death of the parasite within the red blood cells.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, Chloroquine also has sporontocidal activity, which means it can prevent the development of the malaria parasite in the mosquito vector. When a mosquito feeds on a person taking Chloroquine, it reduces the mosquito's ability to transmit the parasite to other individuals. This dual action makes Chloroquine a valuable tool in both the treatment of malaria-infected individuals and in the prevention of further transmission.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Pharmacology, Topic: Overview of anti-malarial drugs.","responses":[{"text":"Quinine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloroquine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Artimisinin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atovaquone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15614,"text":"A housewife presents to the clinic with severe abdominal pain and diarrhea which started off as watery but now contains blood in it. Laboratory findings show leukocytes and red blood cells in the stool. She denies having eaten any undercooked food in the past week. Which of the following organisms is most likely involved?","explanation":"**Shigella** is known for causing bacillary dysentery, characterized by abdominal cramps, fever, and bloody diarrhea. \r\n\r\nThe presence of leukocytes and red blood cells in the stool is a hallmark of invasive bacterial gastroenteritis, which is typical of Shigella infection. Shigella species invade the intestinal mucosa, leading to inflammation and ulceration, which explains the bloody diarrhea. The progression from watery to bloody diarrhea is a common feature of Shigella infection.\r\n\r\nEntamoeba histolytica can cause dysentery, but it is a protozoan parasite, and the presentation often includes a history of travel to endemic areas.\r\nHelicobacter pylori is associated with peptic ulcer disease and gastritis, not typically acute diarrhea.\r\nEscherichia coli causes various types of gastrointestinal infections, but certain strains (like EHEC) would be more likely associated with bloody diarrhea, often with a history of undercooked food consumption.\r\nSalmonella species can cause gastroenteritis, but it typically presents with non-bloody diarrhea and is often associated with a history of consuming contaminated food.","reference":"Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 152.","responses":[{"text":"Helicobacter pylori","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Salmonella species","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Shigella species","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Entamoeba histolytica","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Escherichia coli","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15616,"text":"There is a patient with a clear indication of sepsis. He also has marked hypotension. What is the most appropriate management at this point?","explanation":"Sepsis is a life-threatening condition characterized by systemic inflammation in response to an infection. Hypotension, or low blood pressure, is a critical component of septic shock, which is a severe form of sepsis. In septic shock, there is a significant decrease in blood volume and systemic vascular resistance, leading to inadequate tissue perfusion and organ dysfunction.\r\n\r\nThe initial approach to managing septic shock involves **aggressive fluid resuscitation** to restore intravascular volume, improve cardiac output, and maintain tissue perfusion. This is done by administering intravenous fluids, typically crystalloids, to achieve and **maintain a CVP in the range of 8-12 mm Hg.**\r\n\r\nWhile antibiotics are an essential part of sepsis management, they should be administered promptly once the diagnosis is suspected, but fluid resuscitation takes precedence in the initial management.","reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Medicine, Topic: Sepsis and SIRS","responses":[{"text":"Persistent blood transfusions to keep his Hb at \u003e10 g/dl","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Give him a heavy dose of corticosteroids as soon as possible","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Treat the patient with empirical antibiotics after culture and sensitivity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aggressive fluid resuscitation to keep central venous pressure 8-12 mm Hg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15618,"text":"A patient who was diagnosed with AIDS (acquired immune deficiency syndrome) and tuberculosis (TB) 2 years back is admitted for surgery for appendicitis. He is compliant with HIV medications. He completed anti-TB therapy and now his chest x-ray is clear with no pulmonary infiltrates and no bacteria in his sputum. What precautions should be taken?","explanation":"Given that the patient has completed anti-TB therapy, is compliant with HIV medications, and shows no current signs of active TB, there is no indication for contact or airborne precautions, which are more stringent and are typically reserved for patients with suspected or active infectious diseases that are transmitted by these routes.\r\n\r\n**Standard precautions** are the minimum infection prevention practices that apply to all patient care, regardless of suspected or confirmed infection status of the patient, in any setting where healthcare is delivered. These include hand hygiene, use of personal protective equipment (PPE) appropriately (gloves, masks, eyewear), respiratory hygiene/cough etiquette, safe injection practices, and safe handling of potentially contaminated equipment or surfaces in the patient environment.","reference":"Recommendations for Prevention of HIV Transmission in Health-Care Settings. https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00023587.htm. Accessed 23 Apr. 2023.","responses":[{"text":"Single ward with contact precautions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single ward with standard precautions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General ward with contact precautions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single room with contact and airborne precautions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"General ward with standard precautions","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":15619,"text":"A health officer has taken up the challenge to eradicate HIV (human immunodeficiency virus). His team identified groups of high-risk individuals. Which of the following high-risk groups should be intervened first?","explanation":null,"reference":"Dow lecture slides, Infectious module, Community medicine, Topic: AIDS and Sexually transmitted diseases control and prevention.","responses":[{"text":"Men having sex with men","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Neonates","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pregnant women","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sex workers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Professional or paid blood donors","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":15620,"text":"A man presents to the hospital with an altered level of consciousness two hours after falling in the washroom. He has pinpoint pupils with a pulse of 78 beats per minute, a blood pressure of 180/120 mmHg, and a fever of 107°F despite antipyretics. Sponging is also of no use. What is the most likely cause of fever?","explanation":"The clinical picture presented, especially with an altered level of consciousness following a fall, pinpoint pupils, lack of response to antipyretics, and extremely high fever, strongly suggests a central nervous system pathology. A **pontine hemorrhage** (specifically, a bleed in the pons region of the brainstem) is the most consistent with these findings. \r\n\r\nA pontine hemorrhage can directly affect the temperature-regulating centers of the brain, leading to hyperthermia. The pons is also responsible for parasympathetic output, which explains the pinpoint pupils (due to unopposed parasympathetic activity). The hypertension and bradycardia can be explained by the Cushing reflex in response to increased intracranial pressure from the hemorrhage.","reference":"Amorim, Robson Luis Oliveira de, et al. “Current Clinical Approach to Patients with Disorders of Consciousness.” Revista Da Associação Médica Brasileira, vol. 62, July 2016, pp. 377–84. SciELO, https://doi.org/10.1590/1806-9282.62.04.377.","responses":[{"text":"Encephalitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Meningitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pontine hemorrhage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cerebral malaria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22572,"text":"A 25-year-old male presented with fever and abdominal pain. His illness started with low-grade fever and decreased appetite. He has been unwell for the past 7 days and has per rectal bleeding for the last 2 days. Initially, he took per ciprofloxacin for 3 days followed by oral cefixime and azithromycin for 4 days. He was started on intravenous (IV) ceftriaxone. What is the most appropriate diagnostic test?","explanation":"Symptoms such as fever, abdominal pain, decreased appetite, and per rectal bleeding along with the history of antibiotic use, raise suspicion of an infectious cause, particularly a gastrointestinal infection. In such cases, obtaining a stool culture is the most appropriate diagnostic test to identify the causative organism responsible for the gastrointestinal infection.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nBone marrow culture is typically used to diagnose conditions such as hematological malignancies or certain systemic infections, but it is not the first-line investigation in this case.\r\n\r\nWhile a rectal swab can be useful for identifying certain pathogens, a stool culture is a more comprehensive test to evaluate the presence of various bacteria and parasites in the gastrointestinal tract. \r\n\r\nBlood cultures are essential for diagnosing systemic bloodstream infections, but in this case, the primary concern is a gastrointestinal infection with per rectal bleeding. A stool culture is more specific for identifying the pathogens causing gastrointestinal symptoms.\r\n\r\nWhile a complete blood count (CBC) with peripheral smear can provide valuable information about the patient's overall health, it is not the most specific test for identifying the causative agent of gastrointestinal symptoms and per rectal bleeding.","reference":"(1) Penman ID, Ralston S, Strachan MWJ, Hobson RP. Davidson’s Principles and Practice of Medicine. 24th ed. Elsevier; 2022: 265.\r\n\r\n(2) Levinson W, Chin-Hong P, Joyce EA, Nussbaum J, Schwartz B. Review of Medical Microbiology and Immunology: A Guide to Clinical Infectious Diseases. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2018: 153.","responses":[{"text":"Rectal swab for culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood culture","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stool culture","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Complete blood picture with peripheral film","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bone marrow culture","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

